children.text:
• noun
-a return on a shot that seemed impossible to reach and would normally have resulted in a point for the opponent

• verb
-make (offspring) by reproduction
-Synonyms: beget,bring_forth,engender,father,generate,mother,sire
-Examples:
  + Abraham begot Isaac
  + John fathered four daughters

• verb
-undergo (as of injuries and illnesses)
-Synonyms: have,suffer,sustain
-Examples:
  + She suffered a fracture in the accident
  + He had an insulin shock after eating three candy bars
  + She got a bruise on her leg
  + He got his arm broken in the scuffle

• verb
-be stricken by an illness, fall victim to an illness
-Synonyms: contract,take
-Examples:
  + He got AIDS
  + She came down with pneumonia
  + She took a chill

• verb
-come to have or undergo a change of (physical features and attributes)
-Synonyms: acquire,develop,grow,produce
-Examples:
  + He grew a beard
  + The patient developed abdominal pains
  + I got funny spots all over my body
  + Well-developed breasts

• verb
-give certain properties to something
-Synonyms: make
-Examples:
  + Get someone mad
  + She made us look silly
  + He made a fool of himself at the meeting
  + Don't make this into a big deal
  + This invention will make you a millionaire
  + Make yourself clear

• verb
-cause to move; cause to be in a certain position or condition
-Synonyms: have,let
-Examples:
  + He got his squad on the ball
  + This let me in for a big surprise
  + He got a girl into trouble

• verb
-enter or assume a certain state or condition
-Synonyms: become,go
-Examples:
  + He became annoyed when he heard the bad news
  + It must be getting more serious
  + Her face went red with anger
  + She went into ecstasy
  + Get going!

• verb
-take the first step or steps in carrying out an action
-Synonyms: begin,commence,get_down,set_about,set_out,start,start_out
-Examples:
  + We began working at dawn
  + Who will start?
  + Get working as soon as the sun rises!
  + The first tourists began to arrive in Cambodia
  + He began early in the day
  + Let's get down to work now

• verb
-receive a specified treatment (abstract)
-Synonyms: find,incur,obtain,receive
-Examples:
  + These aspects of civilization do not find expression or receive an interpretation
  + His movie received a good review
  + I got nothing but trouble for my good intentions

• verb
-grasp with the mind or develop an understanding of
-Synonyms: catch
-Examples:
  + Did you catch that allusion?
  + We caught something of his theory in the lecture
  + Don't catch your meaning
  + Did you get it?
  + She didn't get the joke
  + I just don't get him

• verb
-be a mystery or bewildering to
-Synonyms: amaze,baffle,beat,bewilder,dumbfound,flummox,gravel,mystify,nonplus,perplex,pose,puzzle,stick,stupefy,vex
-Examples:
  + This beats me!
  + Got me--I don't know the answer!
  + A vexing problem
  + This question really stuck me

• verb
-reach by calculation
-Examples:
  + What do you get when you add up these numbers?

• verb
-cause to do; cause to act in a specified manner
-Synonyms: cause,have,induce,make,stimulate
-Examples:
  + The ads induced me to buy a VCR
  + My children finally got me to buy a computer
  + My wife made me buy a new sofa

• verb
-move into a desired direction of discourse
-Synonyms: aim,drive
-Examples:
  + What are you driving at?

• verb
-communicate with a place or person; establish communication with, as if by telephone
-Examples:
  + Bill called this number and he got Mary
  + The operator couldn't get Kobe because of the earthquake

• verb
-take vengeance on or get even
-Synonyms: fix,pay_back,pay_off
-Examples:
  + We'll get them!
  + That'll fix him good!
  + This time I got him

• verb
-succeed in catching or seizing, especially after a chase
-Synonyms: capture,catch
-Examples:
  + We finally got the suspect
  + Did you catch the thief?

• verb
-reach with a blow or hit in a particular spot
-Synonyms: catch
-Examples:
  + The rock caught her in the back of the head
  + The blow got him in the back
  + The punch caught him in the stomach

• verb
-go or come after and bring or take back
-Synonyms: bring,convey,fetch
-Examples:
  + Get me those books over there, please
  + Could you bring the wine?
  + The dog fetched the hat

• verb
-attract and fix
-Synonyms: arrest,catch
-Examples:
  + His look caught her
  + She caught his eye
  + Catch the attention of the waiter

• verb
-overcome or destroy
-Examples:
  + The ice storm got my hibiscus
  + The cat got the goldfish

• verb
-earn or achieve a base by being walked by the pitcher
-Synonyms: draw
-Examples:
  + He drew a base on balls

• verb
-apprehend and reproduce accurately
-Synonyms: catch
-Examples:
  + She really caught the spirit of the place in her drawings
  + She got the mood just right in her photographs

• verb
-evoke an emotional response
-Examples:
  + Brahms's `Requiem' gets me every time

• verb
-irritate
-Synonyms: get_under_one's_skin
-Examples:
  + Her childish behavior really get to me
  + His lying really gets me

• verb
-reach a destination; arrive by movement or progress
-Synonyms: arrive,come
-Examples:
  + She arrived home at 7 o'clock
  + She didn't get to Chicago until after midnight

• verb
-reach and board
-Examples:
  + She got the bus just as it was leaving

• verb
-leave immediately; used usually in the imperative form
-Synonyms: bugger_off,buzz_off,fuck_off,scram
-Examples:
  + Scram!

• verb
-go through (mental or physical states or experiences)
-Synonyms: experience,have,receive
-Examples:
  + Get an idea
  + Experience vertigo
  + Get nauseous
  + Receive injuries
  + Have a feeling

• verb
-receive as a retribution or punishment
-Synonyms: receive
-Examples:
  + He got 5 years in prison

• verb
-suffer from the receipt of
-Synonyms: catch
-Examples:
  + She will catch hell for this behavior!

• verb
-perceive by hearing
-Synonyms: catch
-Examples:
  + I didn't catch your name
  + She didn't get his name when they met the first time

• verb
-purchase
-Examples:
  + What did you get at the toy store?

• verb
-come into the possession of something concrete or abstract
-Synonyms: acquire
-Examples:
  + She got a lot of paintings from her uncle
  + They acquired a new pet
  + Get your results the next day
  + Get permission to take a few days off from work

• verb
-achieve a point or goal
-Synonyms: have,make
-Examples:
  + Nicklaus had a 70
  + The Brazilian team got 4 goals
  + She made 29 points that day

• verb
-acquire as a result of some effort or action
-Examples:
  + You cannot get water out of a stone
  + Where did she get these news?
